subSubSection.paragraph:
Male. Stridulatory file slightly sinuate, 
2.54–2.85 mm
long; teeth densely arranged, near apex very dense and small (
Fig. 94
); with about 150–185 teeth or 58–65 teeth per mm; in middle 42–53 teeth per mm. Mirror of right tegmen roughly rectangular, longer than wide (2.67–3.10: 
2.17–2.36 mm
); apical vein substraight, oblique (
Fig. 84
). Cerci narrow elongate, curved mediad in apical half or third; internal surface behind base with a dorso-ventrally compressed projection which is slightly curved anteriorly, has the apex obtuse but with a spinule at tip and which has on ventral side before apex a shorter conical obtuse projection; the baso-internal process continuing posteriorly into a stout lamella which is gradually ascending to the dorsal surface of the cercus, ends distinctly before apex of cercus and carries a minute spinule on tip; short apical part of cercus behind lamella bent ventrad; apex of cercus obtuse with a small spinule on tip (
Figs. 90–91
).

Titillators sclerotised; closely approached in midline; basal parts broad, subhyaline; apical parts angular with large subhyaline expansion; expansion of apical parts with latero-dorsal margin recurved, with a short strip-shaped dorso-apical projection, at apical margin with a large dark spot (
Figs. 86–89
).

Female. Subgenital plate consisting of a central membranous area and two acute lateral lobes; lateral lobes greatly extended dorso-laterally with extension forming a fold around a deep groove (
Figs. 92–93
).
